Procedure puts new spin on liposuction

Kelly Ruane
For The Pitt News

The University of Pittsburgh
Medical Center is renowned for
research in heart and liver trans-
plants. But the hospital is also
advancing a procedure to transfer
fat from one part of a person’s body
to another.

Doctors at the hospital are
working on a method to improve
liposuction. The procedure, called
fat transfer surgery, can be used as
an elective cosmetic procedure or to
correctmedical defects.

“I think this will prove to be a
real value to the patients,” said Dr.
Dennis Hurwitz, director of
UPMC’s Aesthetic Plastic Surgery
Center.

For children born with birth
defects, such as those who do not
develop enough cheek structure,
doctors can graft fat into the face to

’ restructure it. Fat transfer surgery is

also used on some accident victims.

The primary use of the proce-
dure, though, has been to alleviate
changes in the face caused by
aging. The surgery can plump wrin-

kled skin that has sagged and
caused the face to lose fullness.

During the procedure, surgeons
use syringes to extract fat from
areas such as the abdomen and
thighs. The fat is transferred to a
centrifuge that spins it at high
speed, producing a pure quantity of
fat that can be used as a graft.

“For many years, surgeons have

wanted to move fat as a graft but
were unsuccessful until recently,”
Hurwitz said. " M

There is a low incidence of
complications with fat transfer
surgery. The syringes are inserted
into a small incision, so the wounds
heal quickly and do not scar.

“On a rare occasion there can be
a poor intake of the fat, causing
unevenness or lumpiness, which
can be easily corrected with touch-
up work,” Hurwitz said.

In the past, face lifts were the
common way to achieve a desired
look. Fat transfer has the advantage
of giving a more natural appear-
ance. Now the goal for surgeons is
to find out_how to best combine the
two procedures. ‘

Fat transfer surgery is not wide-

ly practiced in the United States,
due to a lack of surgeons skilled in
the technique.

Hurwitz has successfully per-
formed fat transfer surgery on more
than 100 patients during the last 18

