Joseph Kielec

For The Pitt News

The Pittsburgh EcoForum, a
recently formed consortium that
includes Pitt and several other sur-
rounding institutions that focus on the
study of ecology, continues its inau-
gural Eminent Biologist Lecture
Series tonight.

Stephen J. Hubbell, of Princeton
University, will speak about tropical
rain forest ecology. Hubbell’s talk is
the second in a string of topics by
some of the foremost scientists in the
field of ecology and evolution.

The EcoForum is headed by Dr.
Susan Kalisz, of the department of
biological sciences, who said she
expects the lecture series to be only
the first of many joint ventures
between the institutions. i

Ultimately, the goal of the
EcoForum is to help establish the city
of Pittsburgh and Pitt itself as a
national center for the study of the
interrelationships of organisms and
their natural environment.

The organizations involved in the
EcoForum include Pitt’s department
of biological sciences, the
Pymatuning Laboratory of Ecology,
the Carnegie Museum of Natural
History, . the National Aviary of
Pittsburgh, Phipps Conservatory and
Botanical Gardens, the Garden Club
of Allegheny County, the Pittsburgh
Zoo and the Western Pennsylvania

- Conservancy.

Kalisz said the impetus to start an
organization such as the EcoForum
started four years ago, when she first
came to the University. She was
amazed by the wealth of institutions
devoted to the natural sciences in and
around the city, but described the area
as having “many different venues
with little interaction.”

This dearth of interaction between
the institutions led to the development
of the EcoForum, which will serve to
bring the organizations together to
better utilize their resources for
research.

