LIPO

working with a new liposuction
technique, a procedure made readi-
ly available during the early 1980s
that is generally an elective cosmet-
ic surgery to improve a person’s
body contour.

Over 200,000 people per year in

FROM PAGE 1

the United States have liposuction. '

“It is the most popular cosmetic
procedure done today,” Hurwitz
said.

The new method, called
Ultrasonic Assisted Liposuction,
involves a probe that is inserted
through a small incision. The probe
is. connected to a handle that
vibrates at such a high frequency
that fat dissolves when the probe
touches it. The fat is then drained
using a low—pressure suction.

Traditional liposuction is per-
formed by inserting a cannula — a
pipe with holes in both ends used to
drain ﬂuids from body cavities —
through an incision. Surgeons probe
the problem areas. with the cannula,
using a high-pressure suction to
pull out fat in small amounts.

The new procedure has noted
benefits, ‘such as reduced blood
loss. It also removes more fat with
greater safety and speed, without
traumatizing ‘blood vessels and
other body structures. The new pro-
cedure allows for greater access to
areas such as the back, hips, chest
and abdomen that were difficult to
reach with traditional liposuction.

“As with the majority of surgi-
cal procedures, UAL can have sig-
nificant hazards if not performed
with the greatest ofcare,” Hurwitz
said. ' V

The Ultrasound Assisted
Liposuction Task Force has been
studying the new procedure since
1995, with the goal of establishing
safe guidelines for the procedure.
The group is made up of representa-
tives of three leading plastic
surgery organizations: the
American Society of Aesthetic
Surgery, the Lipoplastic Society,
and the American -Society of Plastic
and Reconstructive Surgeons.

The task force also provides

input to the Food: and Drug
Ad-ministration, which must
approve all new surgical proce-
dures.

8‘ Education of the new liposuc-
tion procedure ‘is one of the most
important roles the task force plays,

said Hurwitz, who is a member. He

has been teaching classes for the

task force since February of 1997. 

Hurwitz discussed his experi-
ence with the new liposuction pro-
cedure and with fat transfer surgery
at two seminars held in Newport,

fR.I., in October.

