Suspension of 5-year-old
dressed as firefighter ridiculous

FiVe—year—old Jordan Locke,
dressed in his ﬁreﬁghter costume for
Halloween, was suspended from
Curtisville Elementary for one day
because he violated Deer Lakes
School District’s weapons policy.

The controversy lies in the 5-
inch-long plastic ax that accompanied
the ﬁreﬁghter costume. Jordan’s sus-
pension is especially ridiculous, con-
sideririg he was portraying a heroic
ﬁgure for Halloween, not a psychotic
one.

If Jordan had come to school
with a plasticmeat cleaver, dressed
up as Geoﬁrey Dahmer, with sheep
intestines in his" lunchbox, it might be
a different story. But by dressing up
as a ﬁreﬁghter, a person who saves
lives, he hardly deserves to be pun-
ished.

Curtisville Elementary principal
Janet Ciramella said the Deer Lakes
School District does not “want to
encourage children to play with
weapons, and [does not] want to"
encourage a tolerance for violence.”
Irnitating a ﬁreﬁghter and bringing a
5-inch-long plastic ax is hardly
encouraging violence.

The Deer Lakes School District
is the only party linking the ax to mur-
der. According to ’Jordan’s mother,

' , Annette Locke, she didn’t know how

to tell Jordan he’d miss school on

Monday, since he loves it so much.
By suspending Jordan for one day,
the school is giving him a negative
View of ﬁreﬁghters and axes.

The ax, as used by theﬁreﬁghter,
is a tool of salvation, not ,a tool of
death. The motive behind Jordan’s
bringing an ax to school is totally dif-
ferent from the motive behind some-
one who would have brought a gun.
If Jordan had dressed up as a carpen-
ter, would the school have suspended
him for bringing a plastic hammer
and screwdriver? The school is teach-
ing him — at the impressionable age
of ﬁve — that an ax automatically
equals violence.

Mrs. Locke was not aware Deer

Lakes School District had sent a letter ‘

to all parents stating that children
were not allowed to bring anything
resembling a weapon. The letter did
not explicitly state that an ax was con-
sidered to be a weapon, but even if it
did, bringing plastic replicas of
weapons to school is hardly encour-
aging violence.

Such policies are in place
because of actual violence on school
property — such as the Peduca, Ky.,
and Edinboro, Pa., school shootings.

However, enforcing such a strict
policy on violence on a kindergarten
child, in a situation in which he didn’t
know any better, is utterly ridiculous.

