If you want students to come to
the game (and nobody can deny the
fact that such a goal is desirable), it
must be held on a more reasonable
date.

The main reason this year’s
game was moved is because history
has shown that when Oakland is
empty, so is Pitt Stadium. Nobody
enjoys driving in Oakland, and even
fewer people enjoy trying to park
here.

Without the students around,
there isn’t much reason for anybody
to be in Oakland for anything,
including a football game. Three
Rivers Stadium is a more conve-
nient site for a game for anybody
who lives in a part of Pittsburgh
besides Oakland. The only good
reason for keeping this game (or,
for that matter, any game) in
Oakland is because that’s where
Pitt’s campus is. But what good is a
campus without students?

The tragedy here is that the
whole discussion about the proper
site for the game could be avoided
by changing the date so that stu-
dents would be -here, and this would
look like a real campus. You’ll
notice that there was no suggestion
of moving the Penn State game to
Three Rivers. In fact, Pitt tried that
back in the ‘70s. All of the games
Pitt played at Three Rivers took
place within a week of
Thanksgiving. The experiment was
such a rousing success that after
three years, the series was moved
back to Pitt Stadium.

It’s time to move the West
Virginia game, and not just to the
north shore. It may be a tradition to
play it the day after Thanksgiving,
but that doesn’t make it an intelli-
gent decision. The date certainly
doesn’t add anything to the rivalry,
and it probably detracts from it.
Play the game a week sooner. Or a
week later. Play it on Halloween.
Make it the first game of the season.
Or the last game. Just play it when
we can watch.

Geoff Moak is a columnist for The

Pitt News.

